Actually, while it may not matter to you or your friends in 5 years time, it will still matter to the students whose ability to reach university is impeded by their earlier eduction. You may think that the debate is "stupid" because you worked hard at private school but this argument is not based off of how hard we all‚Ä¶ More worked. You have to work hard to get into top universities like UCL whether you went to private school or state school. There is no argument about that. However, the standard that state schools are held to is much lower than that which private schools are held to, meaning that students are not given the same opportunities and their educational experience does not match that which is given in private schools. I get that a lot of people are making this debate about hard work, admittedly because a lot of us are jealous of the increased opportunities available to students who go to private schools, but it is inherently about equality of opportunity.

Why is it that people say you can't be racist to white people? Whilst I agree white people do not suffer from structural racism (which I think to be the worst form of racism) which other races do, I still think you CAN be racist to white people. In fact, I think you can be racist to anyone. Google says the definition of racism is:‚Ä¶ More prejudice, discrimination, or antagonism directed against someone of a different race based on the belief that one's own race is superior. And I see no reason as to why white people cannot fit into that. Yes, obviously it isn't structural racism like I said, but there are people who joke about white people but then become sensitive when people make jokes about their own race. I just don't agree with the hypocrisy. Why can't we just all get along and stop stereotyping each other.

Tbh Paramore were really snubbed at the Grammys and I'm still mad, After Laughter was a work of pure genius. We got one half of the Farro brothers back, but little did we know that Hayley's marriage was virtually over and that she's been dealing with major anxiety over the past 3 years after selftitled reached major pop radio highs and‚Ä¶ More she's afraid she has peaked - her lyrics were raw, honest and totally heartbreaking, while the synths and beats throughout were totally bop-worthy. Every time you listen through again, you hear something new and and realise just how much betrayal and just pure shit she's had to take from men in her life for the past decade. Just the fact that so many tracks sound happy while having lyrics that are depressing as hell is so damn poetic and I relate to it so deeply. 2017 was the year of revival for old pop punk and emo bands, and Paramore definately led the way, I'm so sad they didn't receive the recognition they deserved.

> Since there's been some posts about body positivity, as well as some news articles, I thought I would say this: I know it's a sensitive issue for people, and of course no one should have to feel awful about their image. But 'bodypositivity' can also lead to the trap of embracing an unhealthy life. Being very overweight has clear‚Ä¶ More risks and dangers associated with it, not to mention costs to others in the form of socialized healthcare. It's fine to be positive about yourself, but it would be foolish to use that as a reason to do nothing about your weight. Pretending that there's no problem, or implying that being overweight is just "another shape" is wrong, because that involves lying to yourself and to others. Being honest with yourself is the first step towards living a healthier life. Sources: I was reasonably overweight for a number of years.

Why are gender identity and sexuality grouped under the same term 'LGBTQ+'. I say this as a gay man who is a supporter of the trans community. While both communities still have a long way to go in terms of equality, the LGB definitely has a lot more recognition and has received a lot more attention in recent years, whilst I feel it is‚Ä¶ More much harder to be a member of the trans community in today's society. I worry that we hail LGBT progress when we are actually only really seeing progress for the LGB community and the trans community is being left behind. But because they all come under the same banner we forget about trans issues. Also sexuality and gender identity are two completely separate issues. Yes, gay people can support the trans community (and vice versa) but we will never truly understand what it means to question your gender identity. The label LGBTQ+ feels to me like "Oh these people aren't 'normal' let's shove them all under the same label".
